{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491140"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:34:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:34:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"843"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/843"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.23,0.06,0.49,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110666"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/843"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92913"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"354"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15363"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16116"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110666"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of progressive difficulty in swallowing. Her symptoms have worsened over the last three months, and now she only consumes fluids. When she lies recumbent, she can feel fluid coming back into her mouth. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her BMI is 23 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pharyngeal pouch","Carcinoma of the oesophagus","Epiphrenic diverticulum","Achalasia","Eosinophilic oesophagitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eachalasia\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features supporting this diagnosis are the long-standing history of dysphagia (two years), progressive worsening of symptoms, and regurgitation of undigested food or fluid, especially when lying down. Achalasia is characterised by impaired relaxation of the lower oesophageal sphincter and loss of peristalsis in the distal oesophagus, leading to these symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a shorter history of dysphagia, usually a few weeks to a couple of months, with rapid progression. The long duration of symptoms in this case makes malignancy less likely, although it cannot be entirely ruled out without further investigation. It is certainly the most important diagnosis to consider (and subsequently exclude), but it is not the \u003Cem\u003Emost\u003C/em\u003E \u003Cem\u003Elikely\u003C/em\u003E diagnosis for this patient. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E (Zenker\u0027s diverticulum) is usually associated with coughing after ingestion of food and the regurgitation of undigested food particles. It typically affects the cervical oesophagus and would not cause such prolonged and progressive dysphagia for both solids and liquids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiphrenic diverticulum\u003C/strong\u003E is an outpouching of the distal oesophagus. While it can cause dysphagia, it is often asymptomatic or causes only mild symptoms. The degree of dysphagia described in this case would be unusual for an epiphrenic diverticulum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic oesophagitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects younger patients and is characterised by intermittent dysphagia and food bolus obstruction. The chronic, progressive nature of the symptoms in this case is less consistent with eosinophilic oesophagitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the diagnosis of achalasia is most likely based on the clinical presentation, further investigations such as barium swallow, manometry, and endoscopy would be necessary to confirm the diagnosis and rule out other potential causes of dysphagia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most patients with achalasia have a history of dysphagia that may stretch back many months or years.","Regurgitation of undigested food or liquid is a common symptom in achalasia, occurring in about 80% of patients.","Achalasia is characterised by impaired relaxation of the lower oesophageal sphincter and loss of peristalsis in the distal oesophagus."],"references":["Stavropoulos SN, Friedel D, Modayil R, Parkman H. Diagnosis and management of esophageal achalasia. BMJ\u00a02016;353:i2785. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27625387/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92913"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"843"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92913"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-02T19:55:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T19:55:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"843"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110666"}}},"meta":{"c